Analyzing Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Jaslin Kaur Sandhu¶

Introduction¶

Ford's GoBike was launched across the San Franciso Bay Area and is available to all residents using either physical Bay Area transit Clipper cards or the Ford GoBike app. Begining in August 2013, Bay Wheels system had over 2600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose.

The Bay Wheels fleet consists of two kinds of bicycles: a "Classic" docked model with a step through frame and a hybrid which is an electrical-assist model that can be parked at a dock or used in a dockless manner. These bicycles are readily available 24 hours a day, 365 days a year and customers can choose from a single ride or to subscribe to an annual membership.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset consists of Ford GoBike rides that took place in the San Franciso Bay Area. The dataset contains detailed features about :

  • Duration : Duration of the bike was booked in seconds.
  • Start Time & End Time : Consists of date and time the user has booked the bike for.
  • Stations : The start and the end of where the rider books the bikes.
  • Customer Data : Data such as gender,birth data and the type of user.

This dataset was further enhanced and values such as age of the user and day of the week the user use the bike is derived from the given data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The are two features of interest in the Ford GoBike dataset is the duration of biking in relation to day of the week and time of the day and the age of the user and the biking time.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Features that would help me support my dataset :

  • Duration of the biking
  • member_birth_year - To derive the age and investigate the relationship between age and biking durations.
  • start_time - To investigate when are the bikes usually used.
  • member_gender - To investigate the gender's of the people that use the bikes most frequently.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  1. The unsual points faced was that the max age was 141. Hence this was adjusted and the dataset of 60 years and below was taken
  2. The duration was not normally distributed. Hence, a log scale was used to scale the dataset to ensure is it more realistic.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  1. An Interquartile range was calculated on the age and the the datset of user types of 60 and below was analysed based on that.
  2. A log scale was used to scale the dataset to ensure is it more realistic.

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30,15))

#Query for Customer Related Data
customers = df_clean.query('user_type == "Customer"')

#Grouping by Start time hour and the day of the week
cust_count = customers.groupby(['start_time_hour', 'start_time_day_ofthe_week']).size()
cust_count = cust_count.reset_index(name='count')
cust_count = cust_count.pivot(index='start_time_hour', columns='start_time_day_ofthe_week', values='count')

#Plotting Heatmap
sb.heatmap(cust_count,  cmap="YlGnBu");

#To ensure the hours start at 0 to 24
ax.invert_yaxis()

#Graph labels

plt.xlabel('Day of Week', fontsize=20);
